{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f9e5a496-0913-49fb-bfa8-746acad9efdd","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the cpu-sampling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar or ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container).\n- For flame-graph style output, add `--format speedscope`.\n- For very high-CPU scenarios where `dotnet-trace` itself is slow, fall back to `perf record -g -p <PID>` (requires `perf` + `SYS_ADMIN` / `perf_event_open` capability).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"781dbf8d-1dd4-42c4-97f6-e2c835a41d19","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"5042:243E33:2141B6:298504:69F55210"},"id":"c71eacb9-21e0-477a-a7cb-48e62a219c02","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:23:37.694Z","parentId":"d0128eb2-d7c7-43de-96ce-83d53085abe2"}
